1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,000
There's a problem that every conference speaker faces:

2
00:00:08,300 --> 00:00:12,050
how do I know how much time I have left

3
00:00:12,350 --> 00:00:14,350
without staring at the director?

4
00:00:14,650 --> 00:00:17,275
The classic solution is a floor clock,

5
00:00:17,575 --> 00:00:21,325
or a hand signal from the back of the room.

6
00:00:21,625 --> 00:00:24,250
Both work — but neither is elegant,

7
00:00:24,550 --> 00:00:28,300
and neither is visible if the speaker is moving around

8
00:00:28,600 --> 00:00:30,600
or focused on a slide.

9
00:00:30,900 --> 00:00:33,150
CueDeck's Stage Timer solves this cleanly.

10
00:00:33,450 --> 00:00:35,700
It's a full-screen, colour-coded countdown that

11
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:39,375
you put on any screen facing the speaker —

12
00:00:39,675 --> 00:00:43,425
a tablet on the lectern, a monitor at the back

13
00:00:43,725 --> 00:00:47,850
of the stage, a TV at the side of the room.

14
00:00:48,150 --> 00:00:50,400
The speaker glances at it and

15
00:00:50,700 --> 00:00:52,950
instantly knows exactly where they stand.

16
00:00:53,250 --> 00:00:55,250
No director intervention required.

17
00:00:55,550 --> 00:01:00,425
Let's set one up and walk through every state it can be in.

18
00:01:00,725 --> 00:01:04,850
The Stage Timer is a display mode in CueDeck's signage system.

19
00:01:05,150 --> 00:01:08,900
That means you create it exactly like any other display:

20
00:01:09,200 --> 00:01:13,325
open the Signage panel in the director console, click Add Display.

21
00:01:13,625 --> 00:01:18,125
Give it a name — something like 'Stage Timer — Main Hall'.

22
00:01:18,425 --> 00:01:20,425
Set the zone to 'stage'.

23
00:01:20,725 --> 00:01:24,475
Set orientation to portrait if you're using a tablet or

24
00:01:24,775 --> 00:01:28,525
a vertical monitor — the layout is designed to work

25
00:01:28,825 --> 00:01:32,575
well in both orientations, but portrait is particularly good for

26
00:01:32,875 --> 00:01:35,875
a tablet on a stand at the lectern.

27
00:01:36,175 --> 00:01:38,175
For content mode, select 'stage-timer'.

28
00:01:38,475 --> 00:01:40,475
Hit Save.

29
00:01:40,775 --> 00:01:42,775
The display card appears.

30
00:01:43,075 --> 00:01:45,700
Now click Open to get the URL.

31
00:01:45,1000 --> 00:01:47,1000
There it is.

32
00:01:48,300 --> 00:01:50,300
A large, full-screen timer.

33
00:01:50,600 --> 00:01:54,350
Right now it's showing the standby state because we haven't

34
00:01:54,650 --> 00:01:56,650
started a session yet.

35
00:01:56,950 --> 00:01:59,950
Let's go through each state one by one.

36
00:02:00,250 --> 00:02:02,875
When no session is currently LIVE or

37
00:02:03,175 --> 00:02:06,550
on HOLD, the stage timer shows the standby state.

38
00:02:06,850 --> 00:02:09,475
If there's a session coming up —

39
00:02:09,775 --> 00:02:12,400
in READY, CALLING, or PLANNED state —

40
00:02:12,700 --> 00:02:16,075
the display shows 'NEXT UP IN' at the top,

41
00:02:16,375 --> 00:02:20,125
a large countdown to that session's scheduled start time in

42
00:02:20,425 --> 00:02:23,050
the centre, and the session title and

43
00:02:23,350 --> 00:02:25,350
speaker name at the bottom.

44
00:02:25,650 --> 00:02:29,400
This is what the speaker sees as they're preparing backstage

45
00:02:29,700 --> 00:02:31,700
or walking to the lectern.

46
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:35,750
They can see exactly how many minutes until their session

47
00:02:36,050 --> 00:02:39,800
begins, and confirm they're looking at the right session title.

48
00:02:40,100 --> 00:02:43,850
The moment a director clicks Go Live in the production

49
00:02:44,150 --> 00:02:46,400
console, the stage timer updates automatically.

50
00:02:46,700 --> 00:02:50,450
Supabase pushes the state change via its realtime channel and

51
00:02:50,750 --> 00:02:53,000
the display re-renders within a second.

52
00:02:53,300 --> 00:02:56,300
The green state: clean, calm, plenty of time.

53
00:02:56,600 --> 00:02:59,600
The status badge at the top reads LIVE.

54
00:02:59,900 --> 00:03:02,900
The timer in the centre is enormous —

55
00:03:03,200 --> 00:03:06,950
we're talking the size that's readable from across a room.

56
00:03:07,250 --> 00:03:09,500
Below it, a label reading 'REMAINING'.

57
00:03:09,800 --> 00:03:13,175
Underneath the timer, the session title and speaker name.

58
00:03:13,475 --> 00:03:17,225
And at the very bottom, a small 'NEXT:' line showing

59
00:03:17,525 --> 00:03:21,275
the title of the next session in the programme —

60
00:03:21,575 --> 00:03:24,200
so the speaker knows what's following them.

61
00:03:24,500 --> 00:03:28,250
There's also a progress bar running across the width of

62
00:03:28,550 --> 00:03:33,425
the screen, filling from left to right as the session time is consumed.

63
00:03:33,725 --> 00:03:35,975
It's a visual secondary indicator —

64
00:03:36,275 --> 00:03:38,525
useful for peripheral awareness even when

65
00:03:38,825 --> 00:03:42,575
the number itself is hard to read at a distance.

66
00:03:42,875 --> 00:03:46,625
At five minutes remaining, the timer colour shifts to amber.

67
00:03:46,925 --> 00:03:50,300
No animation, no flash — a clean, smooth transition.

68
00:03:50,600 --> 00:03:54,725
The label below the timer changes from 'REMAINING' to 'WRAPPING UP'.

69
00:03:55,025 --> 00:03:58,025
The progress bar also turns amber to match.

70
00:03:58,325 --> 00:04:03,200
This is the speaker's cue to start bringing their talk to a conclusion.

71
00:04:03,500 --> 00:04:06,500
They don't need eye contact with the director,

72
00:04:06,800 --> 00:04:09,425
they don't need a hand signal —

73
00:04:09,725 --> 00:04:11,725
the screen is telling them.

74
00:04:12,025 --> 00:04:15,025
At two minutes remaining, the timer turns red.

75
00:04:15,325 --> 00:04:17,325
The label becomes 'ENDING NOW'.

76
00:04:17,625 --> 00:04:19,875
This is the critical threshold —

77
00:04:20,175 --> 00:04:23,550
the speaker has ninety seconds to wrap up and

78
00:04:23,850 --> 00:04:25,850
hand back to the stage.

79
00:04:26,150 --> 00:04:28,775
The red state is hard to ignore.

80
00:04:29,075 --> 00:04:33,200
Even in a bright room, a red full-screen display gets attention.

81
00:04:33,500 --> 00:04:37,250
The progress bar is now nearly full and also red.

82
00:04:37,550 --> 00:04:42,050
When the session runs past its scheduled end time, the timer flips.

83
00:04:42,350 --> 00:04:45,725
The status badge at the top now reads 'OVERTIME'.

84
00:04:46,025 --> 00:04:48,275
The timer stops counting down and

85
00:04:48,575 --> 00:04:52,325
starts counting up — showing a plus sign followed by

86
00:04:52,625 --> 00:04:55,625
the number of minutes and seconds over time.

87
00:04:55,925 --> 00:04:57,925
And the entire timer flashes.

88
00:04:58,225 --> 00:05:00,225
Not subtle.

89
00:05:00,525 --> 00:05:05,025
This is intentional — a speaker in OVERRUN needs an unmistakable signal.

90
00:05:05,325 --> 00:05:09,075
The director in the production console sees the same OVERRUN

91
00:05:09,375 --> 00:05:11,625
status on the session card, and

92
00:05:11,925 --> 00:05:14,550
can choose to nudge the session —

93
00:05:14,850 --> 00:05:17,850
extending its end time by one minute —

94
00:05:18,150 --> 00:05:21,525
if they decide to give the speaker more room.

95
00:05:21,825 --> 00:05:24,825
When a nudge is applied from the console,

96
00:05:25,125 --> 00:05:28,500
the stage timer display picks it up immediately and

97
00:05:28,800 --> 00:05:31,425
the countdown resumes from the extended time.

98
00:05:31,725 --> 00:05:33,975
HOLD is the paused state —

99
00:05:34,275 --> 00:05:38,025
used when AV needs to stop the session clock temporarily.

100
00:05:38,325 --> 00:05:42,450
Maybe there's a technical problem, a fire alarm, an unexpected interruption.

101
00:05:42,750 --> 00:05:46,500
When a session goes on HOLD in the production console,

102
00:05:46,800 --> 00:05:48,800
the stage timer freezes.

103
00:05:49,100 --> 00:05:52,850
The timer stops counting — it holds the exact remaining

104
00:05:53,150 --> 00:05:55,775
time at the moment HOLD was triggered.

105
00:05:56,075 --> 00:05:58,075
The colour shifts to orange.

106
00:05:58,375 --> 00:06:00,625
The status badge changes to 'HOLD'.

107
00:06:00,925 --> 00:06:03,550
The label below the timer reads 'PAUSED'.

108
00:06:03,850 --> 00:06:07,225
This is important: the timer is frozen, not counting.

109
00:06:07,525 --> 00:06:11,650
The speaker and the director both see the same frozen number.

110
00:06:11,950 --> 00:06:14,200
When the session resumes — when

111
00:06:14,500 --> 00:06:17,125
AV transitions it back to LIVE —

112
00:06:17,425 --> 00:06:20,800
the countdown picks up from exactly where it stopped.

113
00:06:21,100 --> 00:06:25,600
Time that was on hold doesn't count against the speaker's remaining time.

114
00:06:25,900 --> 00:06:29,650
The Stage Timer is designed to work in portrait orientation

115
00:06:29,950 --> 00:06:31,950
as well as landscape.

116
00:06:32,250 --> 00:06:36,000
Portrait is ideal for a tablet on a lectern stand

117
00:06:36,300 --> 00:06:40,050
— the long axis of the screen means the timer

118
00:06:40,350 --> 00:06:43,725
can be even larger, and the session title and

119
00:06:44,025 --> 00:06:46,650
next session footer have more vertical space.

120
00:06:46,950 --> 00:06:50,325
To use portrait, just set orientation to portrait when

121
00:06:50,625 --> 00:06:54,375
you create or edit the display in the signage panel.

122
00:06:54,675 --> 00:06:57,300
The display page adapts its layout automatically.

123
00:06:57,600 --> 00:07:00,225
In practice: buy a cheap tablet mount,

124
00:07:00,525 --> 00:07:04,275
prop it on the lectern, open the display URL in

125
00:07:04,575 --> 00:07:06,825
full screen, lock the screen orientation.

126
00:07:07,125 --> 00:07:09,125
That's your speaker timer.

127
00:07:09,425 --> 00:07:12,425
No hardware, no timecode, no dedicated timer device.

128
00:07:12,725 --> 00:07:15,350
One quick note on access: directors and

129
00:07:15,650 --> 00:07:19,400
stage managers can open the Stage Timer display directly from

130
00:07:19,700 --> 00:07:22,700
the context panel in the production console —

131
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:26,375
there's a 'STAGE TIMER' button in the Monitor section,

132
00:07:26,675 --> 00:07:29,300
right next to the Stage Monitor button.

133
00:07:29,600 --> 00:07:34,475
Clicking it opens the configured Stage Timer display URL in a new tab.

134
00:07:34,775 --> 00:07:38,525
If no Stage Timer display has been set up yet,

135
00:07:38,825 --> 00:07:41,450
CueDeck will show a toast notification and

136
00:07:41,750 --> 00:07:45,500
scroll the signage panel into view so you can create

137
00:07:45,800 --> 00:07:47,800
one on the spot.

138
00:07:48,100 --> 00:07:51,475
The Stage Timer is a simple concept executed well.

139
00:07:51,775 --> 00:07:55,150
One URL, open on any screen facing the stage,

140
00:07:55,450 --> 00:07:59,950
and your speakers are self-managing their own time with zero director overhead.

141
00:08:00,250 --> 00:08:04,375
Set it up once, and it runs for the entire event.

142
00:08:04,675 --> 00:08:07,675
Every session transition, every delay, every HOLD —

143
00:08:07,975 --> 00:08:09,975
it all reflects automatically.

144
00:08:10,275 --> 00:08:12,275
That wraps up this episode.

145
00:08:12,575 --> 00:08:16,325
In the next one we're going into the AI agent

146
00:08:16,625 --> 00:08:19,625
modules — the Incident Advisor, the Cue Engine,

147
00:08:19,925 --> 00:08:21,925
and the Post-Event Report Generator.

148
00:08:22,225 --> 00:08:24,225
See you there.
